<TEXT>
the us justice department is investigating 
usair group inc for possible antitrust violations involving its 
operations at greater pittsburgh international airport the company 
said 
in a may 31 action known as a civil investigative demand the 
justice department ordered the company to produce documents and 
other information relating to activities at the airport 
usair said it was informed by the justice department that other 
airlines and other airports are being investigated 
usair group is the parent company of usair which is the largest 
tenant at the pittsburgh airport and handles a substantial number 
of the flights there 
the probes existence was disclosed recently by usair in 
connection with the issuance of 846 million in revenue bonds for 
construction of a new terminal at the airport 
a justice department spokesman frank kelly declined to comment 
on the nature of the investigation he said the civil investigative 
demand is equivalent to a subpoena but does not mean a civil or 
criminal action has been undertaken 
usair spokesman john bronson said the airline would comply with 
the justice departments request and was gathering all relevant 
documents he said he did not know the exact nature of the justice 
department inquiry 
the solicitor for allegheny county which has a business 
relationship with usair relating to the new terminal said the 
request for information appears to be part of a broader probe the 
investigation probably involves fares charged by airlines at hub 
airports said solicitor ira weiss 
a report issued last year by the general accounting office found 
that fares charged at 15 hub airports were about onefourth higher 
than fares charged at 38 other airports served by a larger number 
of carriers 
the study found that fares charged at pittsburgh were as much as 
8 cents per mile more than fares at the 38 airports 
weiss said one aspect of the usair probe involves its dealings 
with the county the airline and the county negotiated a longterm 
lease two years ago for construction of the 592 million terminal 
according to the bond statement the justice department is 
examining possible violations of the sherman act by conduct 
activities or proposed action relating to restrictions on 
facilities at the airport 
the sherman act makes it illegal for companies to restrain trade 
in the united states or with foreign countries or to conspire to do 
so it also prohibits monopolizing trade or commerce in the united 
states or with foreign countries or attempting or conspiring to do 
so 
weiss said he believed the investigation arose out of usairs 
large share of traffic at the pittsburgh airport 
in 1987 the justice department opposed the merger of usair and 
piedmont airlines but dropped its objections after determining the 
consolidation would not hurt competition 
</TEXT>
