<TEXT>
police in many states have a green light to 
use sobriety checkpoints to combat drunken driving but some 
including a supreme court justice say that tactic will not work 
the high court on thursday upheld michigans checkpoint program 
and by extension similar operations in most states 
critics say checkpoints where all motorists heading in one 
direction are pulled over and detained briefly are not as 
efficient as other methods used by police to catch drunken drivers 
or keep them off the road 
we must begin to assure that every community will make 
checkpoints a key element of an allout campaign to finally rid our 
roads of the menace posed by drinking drivers said micky sadoff 
national president of mothers against drunk driving 
we know that checkpoints are one of the most effective weapons 
to combat drunk driving she added 
brian oneill of the insurance institute for highway safety a 
research group funded by the insurance industry agreed 
checkpoints are a very effective way of creating deterrents he 
said we can never catch all the drunks so what we have to do is 
create programs to deter the offenders 
but nadine strossen general counsel of the american civil 
liberties union said police sobriety checkpoints not only trample 
constitutionally protcted privacy rights but are ineffective 
theres not a smidgen of evidence that these tactics are more 
effective than the traditional constitutional method used by 
police officers to observe traffic and stop those cars that raise 
suspicions she said 
its more effective to use the same number of cops to watch 
traffic in areas where drunk driving has been a problem and have 
them look for those who might be under the influence ms 
strossen said 
the high courts vote thursday was 63 and one of the 
dissenters discounted the effect checkpoints have had or will have 
on drunken driving 
sobriety checkpoints are elaborate and disquieting publicity 
stunts justice john paul stevens said quoting various 
statistics from federal studies he concluded the net effect of 
sobriety checkpoints on traffic safety is infinitesimal and 
possibly negative 
the court ruling will have no effect in at least one state 
police in louisiana are barred from setting up sobriety checkpoints 
by their state constitution which affords greater individual 
privacy than does the federal constitution 
and police in michigan may have to wait to reinstate their 
checkpoint program state courts had invalidated it for violating 
the federal constitutions fourth amendment which bans 
unreasonable police searches and seizures 
now the state courts must resolve a challenge based on the 
michigan constitution 
in other decisions thursday the justices 
ruled 54 in a virginia case that hospitals and nursing homes 
may sue in federal court to challenge how a staterun medicaid 
program reimburses their costs 
decided unanimously in a case from massachusetts that the 
federal government may impose severe fines against air polluters 
even when regulators are slow to decide on cleanair proposals 
allowed the bush administration by a 54 vote in a virginia 
case to limit how much welfare aid some needy families receive 
 
</TEXT>
