<TEXT>
a temperance movement is making gains 
in alaskas native communities 
more than 100 villages with large eskimo indian or aleut 
populations have approved alcohol restrictions since 1980 when the 
legislature began enacting laws letting communities ban the sale 
importation or possession of alcohol 
sobriety is not a dirty word any longer there is a real 
spirit in the community that supports change said carla bonney 
health director for 800 athabascan indians living in or near the 
village of tanana 130 miles west of fairbanks 
but temperance laws alone dont eliminate alcohol use 
bootlegging usually is rampant in remote areas where dry 
villages abut wet villages authorities say 
statistics bear out the extent of alaskas alcohol problem 
the state is third behind new hampshire and nevada in 
percapita alcohol consumption says the national institute for 
alcohol abuse and alcoholism the institute says alaskans drink the 
equivalent of 4 gallons of pure alcohol per person each year 
compared with the national average of 288 gallons 
alaska has twice the national average of accidental deaths and 
70 percent are alcoholrelated according to a 1982 state report 
suicide rates in rural alaska quadrupled during the past decade 
and doubled in urban areas state officials believe 80 percent of 
suicide deaths are alcoholrelated 
the alaska judicial council in 1980 linked 100 percent of rural 
murders 80 percent of violent felonies and 56 percent of property 
crimes to alcohol 
alcohol problems are often most acute among natives an 
estimated 30000 eskimos 5000 aleuts and 15000 indians who 
make up about 10 percent of alaskas 500000 population 
nearly half of all native communities have voted for alcohol 
restrictions 72 villages prohibit the sale and importation of 
liquor 21 have outright bans on possession and 11 others have 
either banned sales of liquor or restricted sales to communityrun 
or package liquor outlets 
the sobriety movement once was limited mainly to urban areas 
because thats where the states socialservice agencies operated 
but now its spreading to the countryside said george mundell 
regional program coordinator for the state office of alcoholism and 
drug abuse 
in some cases whole villages are living an alcoholfree life 
he said 
more and more theres an awareness and understanding that 
folks can get ahead of these alcohol problems and that they are 
preventable mundell said 
theresa tiny devlin of the alaska federation of natives 
which set up a commission in 1988 to study alcohol abuse among 
natives said the temperance campaign is starting to really 
blossom 
in tanana tribal leaders and village officials have worked 
together to tackle alcohol problems bonney said onethird of the 
profits from a statelicensed liquor store in the village goes to 
the tribal government for alcohol programs 
liquor store receipts in tanana dropped 40 percent last year 
over the previous year and the number of alcoholrelated accidents 
has fallen dramatically bonney said 
bootlegging and moonshining however remain overwhelming 
problems in remote areas said roy minatra an investigator for the 
alaska state troopers bureau of drug enforcement 
in the western alaska community of kotzebue where the sale of 
liquor is banned a bottle of rum goes for 80 in bethel a bottle 
of whiskey would fetch about 65 
the drugenforcement bureau has assigned two investigators to 
deal with drug and alcohol law enforcement among 160 villages in 
western alaska and state troopers are aggressively promoting a 
yearold reward system to persuade villagers to turn in liquorlaw 
violators for cash 
as much as 250000 is on offer but so far there have been few 
takers because the program is littleknown officials say 
the emphasis on prohibitionstyle laws is not without its 
critics 
prohibition doesnt work said bonney it didnt work for 
the us in the 1920s if people want to drink they are going to 
find a way 
she said lasting change will come only when young people are 
educated about the dangers of alcohol abuse and whole communities 
change their attitudes 
