<DOCNO> AP900615-0026 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
for years the conventional wisdom about 
african countries was that they were not wellsuited for political 
pluralism under democracy political parties would be formed along 
tribal instead of nationalist lines africans were better off under 
oneparty rule 
or so it was thought 
such notions are becoming increasingly anachronistic these days 
as more and more african governments faced with restive 
populations are tinkering with multiparty systems 
it used to be that the handful of democratic countries 
senegal gambia mauritius and botswana were considered the odd 
men out curiosities on a continent of presidents for life and 
predatory military establishments they now seem to be in the 
vanguard of a continentwide movement 
conservative authoritarians such as the ivory coasts felix 
houphouetboigny as well as leftist ideologues like benins mathieu 
kerekou have legalized opposition parties a variety of other 
nations including gabon zaire zambia and tanzania seem to be 
following suit in islamic north africa algeria this week held its 
first free elections in the countrys 28 years of independence 
nigeria which has been under military rule for 20 of its 30 
years of independence is embarked on transition to democratic rule 
the political ferment is partly an outgrowth of what happened 
last year in eastern europe 
the wind that is blowing in the east should not stop in the 
south says jacques pelletier frances minister for cooperation 
and development the same wind has been blowing from latin america 
where a stampede to democracy took place over the past decade 
wisdom comes at 60 said zaires mobutu sese seko after 
announcing in april that he would allow two additional parties to 
compete for power mobutu reportedly had his change of heart after 
seeing on television the bloodsplattered remains of his onetime 
friend and colleague romanias nicolae ceausescu who was executed 
last december 
kwadwo o akpan who heads the washingtonbased angola peace 
fund debunks the notion that singleparty rule has minimized 
ethnic rivalries 
the leaders of these states are very often perceived to have 
permanently installed members of their in group as leaders of the 
party and therefore as rulers of the country akpan says 
accordingly he says the governments policies and its 
pretense of being representative are seen by the vast majority as 
being false 
as in eastern europe the success of africas experiment in 
pluralism is still in doubt because the continents democratic 
roots do not run deep few however underestimate the problems 
associated with the strongman rule most africans have endured for 
the past generation 
chester crocker the reagan administrations top official for 
african affairs traces africas political transformation to 
shocking economic decline as well as the widespread absence 
of political accountability raw abuse of power rampant nepotism 
and corruption and the suppression of nongovernment 
organizations 
crocker says that when africas independence process began in 
the 1960s westerners were far too indulgent of the dictatorial 
regimes that emerged 
we westerners acted as if it would be unfair impolite or 
downright dangerous to expect african systems of governance to meet 
universal norms he says 
south africas nelson mandela who arrives here next week is at 
the center of what could be a revolutionary democratic change away 
from the countrys discredited apartheid system 
last march namibia became independent from south africa with 
timely help from the united nations namibians have managed to 
avoid the oneparty misrule so evident elsewhere in africa namibia 
began independent life as few countries on the continent have 
with an elected government an independent judiciary and numerous 
curbs on executive power 
there is another contrast whites instead of being expelled 
are being encouraged to remain in namibia key ministerial posts 
have gone to whites 
one of africas most noteworthy holdouts against democratization 
is kenyan president daniel arap moi whose kenya africa national 
union has brought stability as well as prosperity 
we are being asked to risk that which we have so painstakingly 
built in order to lead up to some generalized universal 
prescription of political behavior moi has said 
</TEXT>
