the government says it will ask an appeals court 
to throw out the convictions of seven people who served prison 
sentences for allegedly running an ira bomb factory 
the announcement marked the collapse of all the convictions 
stemming from two irish republican army bombings of pubs in 
guildford and woolwich in 1974 in which seven people died 
i dont believe the convictions can be allowed to stand 
home secretary david waddington told the house of commons thursday 
hours earlier englands senior prosecutor told a judicial 
inquiry that the convictions were unsafe and unsatisfactory 
because of questions about the reliability of scientific tests 
which were the core of the prosecution case 
four people convicted of the bombings were released in october 
after the director of public prosecutions said police had lied 
about some evidence 
the mainly roman catholic ira is fighting to end british rule of 
protestantdominated northern ireland and unite the province with 
ireland 
