defense secretary dick cheney in anticipation 
of pentagon budget cuts is freezing military construction for 
another five months and will ask congress to cancel a large number 
of construction projects his spokesman says 
next week cheney is expected to send congress a list of 
military construction projects that he would like to see 
eliminated pentagon spokesman pete williams said thursday 
cheneys move comes as congress has been pressing for sharp 
reductions in pentagon spending and reductions in the nations 
military forces 
his request is expected to cause some controversy on capitol 
hill 
decisions to halt construction projects are seen by some as an 
attack on pork barrel padding of the defense budget but it also 
fuels the debate between those who want to cut pentagon spending 
and lawmakers who want to protect local jobs 
the secretary decided to extend a worldwide freeze on military 
construction in order to help ensure the department proceeds with 
the projects for which there is a genuine need williams said 
cheney will select his candidates for cancellation from a list 
of some 207 projects including the controversial navy home 
ports in texas alabama mississippi and new york 
last month cheney ordered the 207 projects to be reviewed for 
possible cancellation 
because funds for the projects already have been approved the 
secretary must ask congress to withdraw the funding through a 
process known formally as rescission 
williams said he could not say exactly how many of the 207 
projects might be cancelled but added it is fair to say that 
the secretary believes that funding should be cancelled on a 
substantial number of military construction projects 
i would expect a decision on this next week williams said 
the freeze which will run through nov 15 affects more than 7 
billion in construction 
the 207 specific projects under study for cancellation have been 
valued by the pentagon at 12 billion 
cheney first put a freeze on construction in january and 
extended it in april it was due to expire on june 15 
the 207 sites under study included the socalled strategic home 
ports in ingleside texas mobile ala pascagoula miss and 
staten island ny 
the majority of the 207 projects under review were located 
overseas in particular in west germany planned improvements or 
construction of hangars maintenance facilities family housing 
projects schools for military dependents and medical units were 
among the items targeted 
however some of the domestic sites targeted carried hefty price 
tags 
