<TEXT>
ambitious usjapanese trade talks are 
stalled with american officials threatening not to sign a landmark 
agreement if the japanese fail to open further their markets to 
us goods 
the ongoing dispute flared into the open thursday when bush 
administration officials charged that japan was failing to honor 
commitments made in april to attack the root causes of americas 
49 billion trade deficit with japan 
in april both countries signed an interim agreement pledging to 
make fundamental economic reforms to reduce the huge trade 
imbalance between the two economic superpowers 
in the agreement known as the structural impediments 
initiative japan pledged to boost its public works spending and 
move toward breaking up the cozy relationships between japanese 
firms that keep foreign companies from doing business in japans 
market 
the united states pledged to intensify efforts to reduce the 
federal budget deficit improve its education system and boost its 
low savings rate 
the interim report was due to be followed in early july with a 
final report fleshing out the broad commitments and setting up a 
monitoring arrangement to insure compliance 
however talks on the final report have made little progress 
with the us side pushing for specifics to back up the japanese 
promises and the japanese insisting they have gone as far as they 
can go 
