<TEXT>
the soviet union has urged the western 
allies to begin negotiations this fall to get rid of shortrange 
nuclear weapons in europe nato officials said friday 
but alliance diplomats immediately dismissed the suggestion 
saying bargaining on nuclear arms should take place only after 
agreement on an accord to reduce tanks artillery and other 
conventional weapons in europe 
we will stick to our timetable said one diplomat who 
demanded anonymity this is the logical way to proceed first 
things first 
the kremlin has in the past pressed the western nations for 
early talks on nuclear weapons and sources said did so again this 
week in a proposal to the united states in washington 
the soviet union proposed to the united states to start 
negotiations on the elimination of snf shortrange nuclear forces 
in the autumn of this year said florent swijsen spokesman for 
the north atlantic treaty organization 
he said the offer would be discussed by president bush and other 
alliance leaders at a summit july 56 in london 
under the proposal the soviet union wants to negotiate the 
elimination not only of landbased nuclear arms in europe but also 
airlaunched systems the sources said 
it also would like to bring frances independent nuclear arsenal 
into the talks they said france belongs to nato but remains 
outside its joint military structure 
the issue of shortrange nuclear weapons in europe has become 
increasingly controversial with the easing of tensions between nato 
and the sovietled warsaw pact 
the wests battlefield weapons most based in west germany 
would hit targets in nowfriendly countries in eastern europe the 
term shortrange is applied to weapons with ranges of less than 
about 300 miles 
the western allies have agreed that there is a diminishing 
need for shortrange nuclear arms in their arsenal bush earlier 
this year cancelled us plans to build a more powerful version of 
the lance shortrange missile and a modernized 155mm nucleartipped 
artillery shell 
even so the allies have continued to insist the western defense 
requires an appropriate mix of conventional and nuclear arms 
for the foreseeable future 
with a reduction in landbased forces analysts expect nato to 
put more emphasis on airlaunched nuclear systems the united 
states is developing a tactical airtosurface missile tasm 
which would replace gravity bombs a west german official said last 
week however that the bonn government did not want the new 
weapons based on its territory 
nato foreign ministers last week agreed at a meeting in scotland 
to support a bush suggestion for a speedier timetable for 
negotiations on shortrange nuclear forces they said those talks 
could begin shortly after a conventional arms accord was 
concluded 
at a may 1989 summit bush and the other leaders had linked the 
bargaining to implementation of the treaty 
nato diplomats reiterated their latest position 
we have got to complete the cfe conventional armed forces in 
europe agreement and then get on with it said one official who 
like the others demanded anonymity theres enough to digest 
before we get on with snf he said 
another diplomat said the conventional arms talks were quite 
complicated and added we shouldnt complicate them further 
with new topics of negotiation 
a spokesman for the us mission to nato speaking on condition 
of anonymity said we note the continuing large imbalance in 
soviet shortrange nuclear weapons elimination of this imbalance 
is long overdue 
the united states is prepared to enter into talks for the 
reduction of shortrange nuclear systems as soon as the cfe talks 
are completed he said 
the 16 nato nations and the seven of the warsaw pact have said 
they want to strike a conventional arms deal this year although 
western officials have complained about soviet footdragging 
on thursday diplomats in vienna said the two sides were close 
to agreement on overall limits for tanks and armored combat 
vehicles in europe 
moscow and washington already have agreed to limit their 
stationed forces in central europe to 195000 on each side the 
united states would retain an additional 30000 troops in britain 
and southern europe 
