<TEXT>
the worlds two largest 
goldproducing companies said friday they were curtailing 
operations due to the falling price of gold more than 7800 people 
were to lose their jobs as a result 
angloamerican corp of south africa ltd said two of its mining 
companies free state state consolidated gold mines ltd 
freegold and vaal reefs exploration and mining co ltd would 
cut back on their operations 
earlier this week two other mining groups outside the 
angloamerican conglomerate announced job cutbacks involving 1100 
workers 
gold is south africas major industry earning more than half 
the countrys foreign currency 
lionel hewitt managing director of angloamericans gold and 
uranium division said the company had made efforts in recent months 
to maintain existing levels of operation including costreduction 
measures and deferment of expenditures 
despite these efforts at current gold prices and operating 
costs certain mining areas are now incapable of sustaining mining 
operations at their present levels hewitt said 
the price of gold reached a fouryear low of 34625 per ounce 
in new york and london before recovering thursday it was trading 
at 34750 per ounce in new york on friday afternoon 
hewitt said the cutback would take place over the next nine 
months and probably result in the loss of 7800 jobs at freegold 
he said reducing operations at vaal reefs would not necessarily 
involve loss of jobs because workers may be assigned to other 
areas of the mine 
vaal reefs has greater flexibility in the opening of new ore 
reserves than freegold hewitt said 
on wednesday general mining union corp announced its marginal 
operation stilfontein gold mining co ltd would lay off 500 
workers immediately to cut costs in the face of the low gold price 
anglovaal ltd said its loraine gold mines ltd would lay off 600 
workers and reduce production by 10 percent during the next four 
months 
hewitt said angloamerican management had invited discussions 
with union leaders about the curtailments there was no immediate 
reaction from the unions 
the national union of mineworkers the nations largest black 
union representing some 250000 black miners has already declared 
a dispute and asked for arbitration in its annual wage negotiations 
with the mining industry 
south africa has the deepest gold mines in the world and the 
cost of mining increases with the depth 
the relatively cheap labor with an average black miner earning 
from 300 to 400 per month is one reason why south african mines 
can continue to be profitable at great depths 
curtailing mining operations is considered a serious step 
because once a particular shaft is shut down the infrastructure 
often deteriorates rapidly that would make it costly and dangerous 
to start up again when the price of gold rises 
</TEXT>
