<TEXT>
top soviet leaders declared friday they had won 
legislative support for a market economy despite rejection of an 
immediate price increase for bread and demands for a more detailed 
blueprint of the transition 
comments by the head of soviet economic planning and the 
chairman of the legislature both members of the communist party 
politburo reflected the governments shaky approach to reform 
despite months of study 
the government program presented by premier nikolai i ryzhkov 
last month caused panic buying that left halfempty store shelves 
even barer 
yuri d maslyukov the chairman of the state planning 
commission told reporters friday that the supreme soviet 
legislature was right to posptone the first phase of a bread price 
increase ryzhkov proposed for july 1 
the opinion of the government is that probably considering 
the importance of the matter the decision of the session is 
correct maslyukov said we will look into that matter one more 
time because a mistake would cost it the confidence of the 
people 
bread is the staple of the soviet diet and prices have remained 
unchanged for decades 
but president mikhail s gorbachev pushing for the economic 
reform program told soviets on the eve of his summit trip to 
washington that bread is so cheap that children sometimes use 
loaves for soccer balls at the same time the soviet government is 
forced to use up precious hard currency reserves to ensure there is 
enough grain by importing it he said 
maslyukov and supreme soviet chairman anatoly i lukyanov a 
gorbachev protege who fulfills many of the functions of a vice 
president held news conferences friday a day after the 
legislature finished its spring session to give the governments 
evaluation 
the president and the government have been granted the right 
to make necessary decisions to prepare the transition to a market 
economy maslyukov said 
both acknowledged that the government economic plan required 
more work 
it has become clear that new models arent created on the run 
with one wave of the hand lukyanov said time is needed and 
to take into account many other factors and to weigh all the 
details and to think 
its a new revolution in principle of course it needs 
perfecting he said 
the plan presented by ryzhkov had been in the works for months 
but after two weeks of debate the supreme soviet told the 
government to come back with more detailed plans when it reconvenes 
in september 
the plan calls for food prices to be doubled jan 1 rapid 
conversion of stateowned enterprises to stock companies and the 
gradual sale of stocks to the public it would permit certain 
companies and industries to contract directly for their supplies 
and to sell their products in a free market unprofitable firms 
would go bankrupt 
maslyukov reiterated that the country probably would have its 
first nationwide referendum on the economic package but only after 
more detailed plans are presented to the supreme soviet in the fall 
the legislature must approve the plan before it is presented for 
a referendum which likely will include two main questions the 
speed of economic reform and the methods of compensating consumers 
for the higher costs 
asked about another key area of economic change monetary 
reform maslyukov said the soviet ruble would have to be devalued 
several times to bring it closer to market values 
to make the currency convertible on the world market the 
government must drastically cut its budget deficit he said that 
means reducing spending on capital construction defense and 
foreign aid maslyukov said 
by 1993 government plans call for foreign firms to be able to 
reinvest in the soviet union rubles they have earned in the 
country and by 1995 for the ruble to be convertible 
but other soviet economic officials have said that such 
predictions of full convertibility are too optimistic deputy 
premier leonid a abalkin has said that it likely will take many 
years to make the ruble convertible 
