<DOCNO> AP900615-0132 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the chairmen of two congressional committees 
urged energy secretary james d watkins on friday to take new steps 
to improve safety practices at the savannah river nuclear arms 
plant before allowing it to resume operation 
watkins should insist that operators of savannah rivers nuclear 
reactors which make tritium gas for nuclear warheads meet the 
safety standards of the commercial nuclear industry said sen john 
glenn dohio and rep mike synar doklahoma 
it is critical to change the disturbing mindset of 
complacency that has been embedded at the savannah river plant for 
many years glenn said the energy department still has a long 
way to go 
the legislators were responding to a report by the general 
accounting office the investigative arm of congress that said the 
savannah river operation had not yet made sufficient improvements 
in safety practices and attitudes 
the gao report said that under current energy department plans 
the reactor operators at savannah river would not be required to 
meet commercial industry training standards prior to restart 
the report recommended that watkins require westinghouse 
savannah river co which runs the plant for the government to 
carry out a comprehensive plan for changing the safety culture 
there before it resumes reactor operation 
the plant is on a 315squaremile federal reservation near 
aiken sc 
the report also said that efforts to further improve safety 
practices and attitudes in addition to several other management 
and environmental issues could delay the planned restart of 
savannah river reactors by as much as two years 
watkins has said he hopes to have the first of the three active 
savannah river reactors back in operation by january although no 
final restart date has been set the reactors are the nations only 
source of tritium a radioactive gas that must be replenished in 
warheads because it decays at a rate of 55 percent a year 
the reactors were closed down in 1988 because of safety 
mechanical and management problems 
last week two environmental groups the natural resources 
defense council of new york and the energy research foundation of 
columbia sc filed suit in federal court in aiken challenging 
watkins plan for restarting the reactors 
the suit demanded that restart be blocked until the department 
completes construction of a cooling tower for reactor discharges 
or until president bush exempts the plant from the clean water act 
on national security grounds the tower is scheduled for completion 
in 1992 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

