<TEXT>
east german police said friday they arrested 
four west german fugitives striking a major blow to the core of 
west germanys leftist terrorist movement 
all four were arrested late thursday one was later freed 
because charges against her had expired it was not certain whether 
west germany would file the charges again 
the east german government initially said it also had captured 
three other wanted fugitives but retracted that statement late 
friday 
the three people arrested today in leipzig are not the hunted 
red army faction terrorists barbara meyer horst ludwig meyer and 
sabine callsen the governmentrun news agency adn said in a 
brief news flash 
it gave no explanation for the earlier incorrect information 
issued by the interior ministry and did not say whether the three 
arrested were even suspected of being involved in terrorist 
activities 
despite the erroneous report the arrests of the four fugitives 
in frankfurt an der oder and cottbus together with two arrests on 
wednesday were significant for west german authorities 
authorities consider the fugitives to be among the leaders of 
the red army faction terror gang which waged a murderous war 
against west german capitalism in the 1970s and 1980s 
all had been living in east germany under assumed names and 
west german officials said the arrests go a long way toward 
confirming longheld suspicions that east germanys former 
communist government once harbored terrorists 
bonn government spokesman hans klein told reporters the federal 
government had indications for several years that east germanys 
former secret police sheltered the fugitives 
klein said however the indications were vague and that west 
germans would have run into an iron wall had they tried to 
raise the issue with the former east german leaders 
in east berlin interior minister petermichael diestel told a 
news conference he was unable to confirm widespread speculation 
that terrorists had used east germany as a base for attacks 
but he promised to seek prosecution of any former officials who 
harbored the terrorists under the communist regime 
in hamburg conservative west german lawmaker eduard lintner 
demanded the extradition of ousted communist leader erich honecker 
to face charges of having supported terrorism 
authorities identified those arrested thursday as monika 
helbing 36 and ekkehard von seckendorffgudent 49 arrested in 
frankfurt an der oder and werner lotze 38 and christine 
duemlein 41 arrested in cottbus 
ms helbing and seckendorffgudent are married as are lotze and 
ms duemlein 
ms helbing and lotze allegedly were involved in the 1977 
kidnapslaying of west german industrialist hannsmartin schleyer 
and numerous other terrorist crimes 
ms duemline was wanted on charges of being a member of a 
terrorist organization to overthrow the state and an arrest 
warrant was issued for her in 1978 it was dropped in 1988 after 
the warrant expired by law and east german officials she was freed 
after her capture because it had not been renewed 
ekkehard von seckendorffgudent was wanted as a red army faction 
sympathiser as a doctor he had a permanent visitors pass to a 
hamburg prison which authorities said he gave to suspected 
terrorists to visit jailed compatriots 
as east germany and west germany move toward unification the 
countries are cooperating closely now west german wanted posters 
are seen throughout the east and other fugitives among two dozen 
hardcore leaders could be arrested 
the retraction late friday leaves the meyers some of west 
germanys mosthunted fugitives 
the couple is accused of a car bomb attack that killed two 
people and wounded 20 others at the us air forces rheinmain air 
base near frankfurt in august 1985 
