<TEXT>
an air force enlistee was sentenced friday to 10 
years in prison without parole for attempting to sell secrets to 
the soviets 
us district judge sidney a fitzwater imposed the sentence on 
former airman ronald craig wolf 35 who pleaded guilty in february 
to one count of attempting to transfer national defense information 
to the soviet union 
fbi special agent bobby r gillham said agents began 
investigating wolf in 1989 when they received information that he 
intended to sell sensitive classified information to the soviet 
union wolf was arrested in may 1989 after selling information to 
an undercover fbi agent posing as a soviet agent 
wolf enlisted in the air force in july 1974 in dallas he held a 
security clearance and received training in russian before his 1981 
discharge 
he transcribed sensitive communications while serving in the far 
east gillham said 
wolf had been working in automobile sales since his discharge 
the fbi said 
wolf was arrested near the dallasfort worth international 
airport where he had planned to fly to the soviet union to defect 
after meeting with the undercover fbi agent officials said 
</TEXT>
