house democrats criticized savings and loan 
bailout officials friday for hiring highpaid consultants keeping 
executives of failed thrifts on the job and continuing to pay 
others who perform no work 
congress is hearing growing reports of overpaid individuals 
running governmentheld institutions of officers from failed 
institutions staying on the government payroll with sixfigure 
salaries said rep bruce vento dminn chairman of the house 
sampl bailout task force 
at a time when it is reported that the total cost to the 
taxpayer is growing at an everincreasing rate why is the 
resolution trust corp continuing these megadollar salaries for a 
work product that at best is mediocre and at worst is a proven 
failure he asked 
vento cited three cases 
two governmentcontrolled thrifts in orange county calif 
mercury savings and western empire savings continued to pay six 
former officers even though they no longer worked for the 
institutions 
wallace associates a salt lake city firm received 500000 to 
manage midwest savings association in minneapolis for a year 
the managing agent at franklin savings association in ottawa 
kan is receiving 220000 for his first six months on the job 
rtc chief executive officer david cooke said that in the 
california institutions top executives were placed on paid 
administrative leave until their thrifts were placed in 
receiverships and their employment contracts could be legally 
broken 
cooke said the agency usually is able to break such contracts 
swiftly but in the case of some large complex institutions must 
maintain them for several months 
some of these sweetheart management deals they cut for 
themselves are almost ironclad legally said michael j 
martinelli the rtcs regional director in kansas city mo 
in the case of midwest savings the consulting firm was 
replacing even higher paid executives martinelli said the manager 
hired for franklin savings was worth his salary because he had the 
expertise necessary to deal with the thrifts complex securities 
portfolio he said 
cooke said top executives were retained at 211 of 351 thrifts 
seized by the government through april 13 of those salaries 
remained unchanged at 124 were lowered at 51 and raised at 36 
salary reductions for top executives at seized thrifts have saved 
taxpayers nearly 35 million he said 
it is important to understand that in many cases the senior 
management in institutions taken into conservatorship are not 
dishonest or incompetent and are not the ones who caused the 
institution to fail he added 
however rep james mcdermott dwash questioned whether any 
employees of a failed thrift above the level of secretary or teller 
should be retained when a new governmentcontrolled thrift is 
created 
the question is are you allowing the virus that took down 
one sampl to move to the next sampl he said 
