a group of indians from wisconsin tribes told 
county government representatives friday they should negotiate 
settlements to their problems instead of forming a national 
organization to challenge treaties 
to me its sad we cant sit down in our own areas and resolve 
our problems purcell powless chairman of the oneida tribe told 
a meeting run by the wisconsin county association 
whether you like me or not im here and my people are going 
to be here a long time he said 
powless was among 12 tribal representatives who spoke to the 
conference of county officials working to form a national coalition 
on federal indian policy 
i dont believe there is a need for the things they are trying 
to do said joe bresette a chippewa indian and executive 
director of the great lakes intertribal council there is a 
presumption that there is us and them we dont believe that 
trouble erupted at the first meeting of the coalition last 
january in salt lake city because indians were excluded this 
time the coalition organizers complied with the indians desire to 
speak earlier than originally scheduled 
the idea for a coalition arose from a dispute between the 
chippewa indians in wisconsin and 20 counties over timber rights 
the indians say federal treaties give them the right to harvest on 
18 million acres of land the counties claim 
the case is pending in federal court with briefs due june 26 
from both sides on whether the treaties should be reopened 
mark rogacki executive director of the wisconsin county 
association said the dispute led his group to contact counties in 
other states with similar problems 
there are common threads of indian policy that run through the 
country said rogacki we want federal government officials 
to conduct hearings all across the nation to find out what the 
problems are 
he said the issues now in courts could be eliminated if congress 
adjusted the treaties 
eighteen county representatives from five states were at the 
conference which was called to discuss how to get the national 
association of counties to make the coalition a part of its 
activities said rogacki 
rita kenshena tribal attorney for the menominee tribe said she 
and the other indians hoped to stress the need to work locally to 
settle the disputes 
the indian tribes are more informed about their governments 
and treaties than the county officials she said 
keith ferris chairman of the conference said he planned to ask 
the tribes in wisconsin whether they would be willing to 
reestablish a local board that brought together county and tribal 
leaders to discuss the various problems that arise 
