<TEXT>
the justice department on thursday sided with 
the major television networks in their fight to regain the right to 
own or be able to sell their programs in the lucrative rerun market 
the department said it supported a 1983 conclusion by the 
federal communications commission that allowing tv networks to have 
a financial interest and syndication rights in the programs they 
broadcast would not hurt competition 
it appears that in purchasing television entertainment 
programs the networks compete not only with each other but also 
increasingly with other purchasers of television entertainment 
programs the department said in a filing with the commission 
it urged the commission to eliminate the financial interest 
and syndication rules unless the record demonstrates that they are 
necessary to protect the public interest in competition 
the fcc in march said it would reconsider 1970 rules that 
prohibit abc cbs and nbc from having an interest in their programs 
or selling them in syndication 
the fcc had postponed beginning its inquiry until thursday to 
give the interested parties one last chance to work out an 
agreement to alter the rules known as finsyn producers and 
the networks have been engaged in oftenacrimonious talks to change 
the rules ever since 1983 
the talks failed this week again and the commission began 
accepting comments thursday 
fcc chairman alfred sikes who has said he wants some changes in 
the rules said he was disappointed but not surprised that the 
parties did not reach agreement 
the fcc earlier this year granted fox broadcasting co a waiver 
from the finsyn rules so it could continue to grow into a true 
network fox also is a syndicator and it is owned by a major 
hollywood producer twentieth century fox film corp 
fox inc chairman barry diller on thursday in a statement in 
los angeles said there was an urgent need to review the rules 
and to revise the definition of a network he said the fcc should 
be encouraging companies such as fox 
in 1983 the fcc tentatively decided to eliminate the financial 
interest rule and narrow the syndication rule to prohibit only 
network participation in domestic syndication of prime time 
programs but it delayed the proceeding under pressure from 
congress and president reagan and urged the interested parties to 
find a solution themselves 
in march the fcc officially terminated that inquiry and began 
the new one 
networks argue that the finsyn rules give undue market power to 
producers and impede the networks abilities to compete in the 
increasingly multinational program marketplace 
advocates of the rules claim they have helped small producers 
flourish and have led to more diversity in programming 
the justice department told the fcc that if the networks do 
not have significant market power it appears that the practices 
prohibited by the rules would not in these circumstances create 
such power 
it also appears unlikely that the rules significantly 
constrain the exercise of any market power that the networks may 
possess but we cannot conclusively rule out that possibility 
the department conceded it was possible that removing the rules 
could result in wealth transfers from producers to networks 
but this would not warrant retaining the rules unless such 
transfers would be accompanied by an adverse effect on program 
output and thus a decrease in social welfare the department said 
it said increased competition in the program production market 
and efficiencies gained through network ownership of financial 
interests and syndication rights would benefit the public 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

