the opposition social democrats gave 
halfhearted approval thursday to economic merger with east 
germany saying they wont fight it but that chancellor helmut kohl 
is to blame for any untoward consequences 
their action removes the last political obstacle to launching 
the economic and monetary union that takes effect july 2 merging 
the currencies and other economic mechanisms will mark a huge step 
toward formal german unification 
the leftofcenter social democrats made their decision at a 
special leadership meeting on thursday that included oskar 
lafontaine the partys nominee for chancellor in west german 
elections set for dec 2 
lafontaine has harshly criticized the treaty between the two 
germanys but his position deeply divided the social democrats and 
speculation arose that he might quit his candidacy because of 
internal feuding 
lafontaine remains popular however and has decided to stay in 
the race 
party leaders agreed thursday the party should not try to block 
the merger treaty but at the same time they washed their hands of 
any responsibility if the merger brings unwelcome results 
one leader norbert gansel said the party sees economic merger 
as unavoidable and necessary because of the high expectations 
it has produced in east germany but he said the party was not 
offering an uncritical yes 
reading from a leadership statement gansel said kohls 
government will bear sole responsibility if dramatic problems 
arise from the economic merger 
gansel even left the door open for individual party members to 
vote against the merger when the treaty comes up for parliamentary 
ratification on june 21 and 22 he said any lawmaker voting against 
would not be acting outside of solidarity with the rest of the 
party 
experts say up to 2 million east germans could lose their jobs 
as antiquated factories go bust that could produce unrest in east 
germany 
another concern is that west germans will face hefty tax 
increases to pay for rebuilding east germanys economy kohls 
government insists tax increases will not be needed 
for weeks the social democrats tried to get kohls government 
to change the treaty to provide more job protection for east 
germans 
but the party was reluctant to press its objections to the 
merger treaty too strongly lest it anger east germans eagerly 
awaiting the anticipated fruits of economic merger and overhaul of 
the battered east german economy 
the social democrats still want to be in a position to reap a 
political windfall however if kohls economic merger plans 
produce severely negative effects 
