<TEXT>
lets not waste words six degrees of 
separation by john guare is a crackling good play a snappy 
smart tale of manhattan made even more intriguing because it is 
based on a real incident 
the production which opened thursday at the mitzi newhouse 
theater in lincoln center is also wonderfully funny and inventive 
not only in its unexpected plot twists but in the way director 
jerry zaks brings out its darker more serious moments 
guare who used a newspaper story as the starting point for his 
play has created a scathing satiric look at the fads foibles and 
follies of living in manhattan circa 1990 the news article told 
of a hoax involving a young man who claimed to be the son of actor 
sidney poitier and how he duped several prominent new york families 
in guares play just about everyone is a con man even its 
uppercrust liberal hero and heroine flan and ouisa are not 
above pulling a scam of sorts hes an art dealer who courts 
wealthy foreigners you know says the wife the kind of people who 
cant scrape together enough money for dinner but can come up with 
2 million for a secondrate cezanne 
but these east siders meet their match in paul a young man who 
shows up at their apartment the lad claiming to a friend of their 
collegeage children has just been mugged the couple embrace him 
especially after he says he is poitiers son 
the youth cooks dinner for them and is invited to stay he 
promises to introduce them to his father and even get them jobs in 
a movie version of cats that his father allegedly is directing 
he also dazzles them with conversation about his college thesis on 
the catcher in the rye only later do the entranced couple 
learn he is a fraud 
his cover is blown when flans lawyer and his wife tell a 
similar story it seems they were duped by paul the previous week 
and guare adds a third victim a physician who allows paul to stay 
over in his brownstone 
the unraveling of pauls real identity wont be revealed here 
but the detective work involves the children of these wealthy 
people the kids are portrayed as adolescent gargoyles blaming 
their parents for everything that has gone wrong in their lives and 
determined to make them suffer 
guare has captured their revenge hilariously particularly in a 
diatribe for actor evan handler who plays a spiteful son railing 
against his father 
the play then turns serious when pauls flimflam takes in a 
naive couple from utah babes in the big city the consequences of 
his deceptions are tragic guare weaves all the stories together 
the one link being the young man who has been able to affect for 
good and ill so many lives 
the entire cast is firstrate but special mention should be 
made of the three leads stockard channing makes the baffled 
bewildered matron a figure of sympathy by the end of the play john 
cunningham is the epitome of wasp pomposity as her husband james 
mcdaniel is astonishing as paul portraying him as victimizer and 
victim too 
tony waltons stylized set is mostly a series of picture frames 
and a couch or two strewn on the playing area but they work 
brilliantly to suggest a variety of locales including a bench in 
central park 
the odd title six degrees of separation refers to a 
concept articulated by ouisa as she ponders how she and her friends 
were brought in contact with paul everybody on the planet is 
separated from everybody else by only six people she says adding 
that the trick is to find the right six people guare has not only 
found the right people but put them on stage with dazzling results 
</TEXT>
