unlike marcour they both lived in this country 
marcour 47 agreed to pay the us government 2062 in trading 
losses he avoided as well as 358 in interest 
marcours west german lawyer michael siebold was traveling and 
could not be reached for comment sec officials said 
according to the sec complaint marcour who lives and works in 
west germany sold 500 shares of apollo computer inc stock in july 
1988 allegedly with knowledge that apollos sales for that 
quarter would be significantly lower than expected 
at the time marcour was an international sales manager at 
apollos wholly owned european subsidiary apollo domain computer 
gmbh and handled the account of siemens ag a major west german 
electronics company 
harry j weiss an associate director of the secs enforcement 
division said marcour was subject to us securities laws because 
an employee of an american public company who happens to be based 
in a foreign country is under the same legal duties to his employer 
as an americanbased employee of the same company 
apollo computer based in chelmsford mass was acquired by 
electronics giant hewlettpackard co in may 1989 
weiss would not comment on how the sec obtained information 
about marcour the united states does not have a formal cooperation 
agreement on securities law violations with west germany 
he said that even sales managers could be subject to insider 
trading sanctions if they are able to observe information that is 
material but nonpublic not available to the public and then 
trade on it for their own benefit 
