relationship with usair relating to the new terminal said the 
request for information appears to be part of a broader probe the 
investigation likely involves fares charged by airlines at hub 
airports said ira weiss 
a report issued last year by the federal general accounting 
office found that fares charged at 15 hub airports were about 
onefourth higher than fares charged at 38 other airports served by 
a larger number of carriers 
the study found that fares charged at pittsburgh were as much as 
8 cents per mile more than fares at the 38 airports 
weiss said one aspect of the usair probe involves its dealings 
with the county the airline and the county negotiated a longterm 
lease two years ago for the construction of the new 592 million 
terminal 
any time you have the justice department conducting an inquiry 
of this nature its a cause for alarm weiss said 
theres no reason to believe theres anything inappropriate 
about usairs role at the existing terminal or at the new midfield 
terminal and were confident at the conclusion of this proceeding 
that things will proceed as they are he added 
according to the bond statement the justice department is 
examining possible violations of the sherman act by conduct 
activities or proposed action relating to restrictions on 
facilities at the airport 
the sherman act makes it illegal for companies to restrain trade 
in the united states or with foreign countries or to conspire to do 
so it also prohibits monopolizing trade or commerce in the united 
states or with foreign countries or attempting or conspiring to do 
so 
weiss said he thought the investigation arose out of usairs 
large share of traffic at the pittsburgh airport 
in 1987 the justice department opposed the merger of usair and 
piedmont airlines but dropped its objections after determining the 
consolidation would not hurt competition 
