<TEXT>
the worlds two largest gold 
producing companies announced curtailment of their mining 
operations friday due to the plummeting price of gold 
anglo american corp of south africa ltd said two of its mining 
companies free state state consolidated gold mines ltd freegold 
and vaal reefs exploration and mining co ltd would cut back on 
operations in moves that will cut at least 7800 jobs 
earlier this week two other mining groups outside the 
angloamerican conglomerate announced job cutbacks involving 1100 
workers 
the price of gold reached a 4year low of 34625 per ounce in 
new york and london before recovering on thursday gold is south 
africas major industry earning more than half the countrys 
foreign currency 
lionel hewitt managing director of angloamericans gold and 
uranium division said the company in recent months had tried 
several programs to maintain existing operating levels including 
cost reduction measures and deferment of capital expenditure 
despite these efforts at current gold prices and operating 
costs certain mining areas are now incapable of sustaining mining 
operations at their present levels hewitt said 
he said the curtailment of operations would take place over the 
next nine months and probably result in the loss of 7800 jobs at 
freegold he said reductions at vaal reefs would not necessarily 
eliminate jobs because workers may be assigned to other areas of 
the mine 
operating reductions at freegold would reduce its gold 
production by less than 1 percent while the proposed action at 
vaal reefs likely would improve production hewitt said 
on wednesday general mining union corp announced its 
marginally operating stilfontein gold mining co ltd would lay off 
500 workers immediately to cut costs in the face of low gold 
prices anglovaal ltd said its loraine gold mines ltd would lay 
off 600 workers and reduce production by 10 percent in the next 
four months 
hewitt said anglo american management had invited discussions 
with union leaders about the curtailments there was no immediate 
reaction from the unions 
the national union of mineworkers the nations largest black 
union representing some 250000 black miners has already declared 
