<TEXT>
martin a siegel who allegedly took suitcases 
filled with cash from ivan boesky in exchange for inside 
information was sentenced friday to two months in prison 
us district judge robert j ward cited siegels contrition and 
cooperation with prosecutors in giving him one of the shortest 
prison terms meted out in wall streets insider trading scandals 
siegel a mergers specialist for the investment firms drexel 
burnham lambert inc and kidder peabody amp co was one of the 
first wall street figures to cooperate with prosecutors after being 
implicated by boesky the notorious stock speculator 
boesky in recent testimony in another case said he gave siegel 
suitcases of cash for inside information on takeover attempts 
siegel has admitted swapping stock tips with former goldman sachs 
amp co trader robert freeman 
over the last three and a half years i have tried to do 
everything in my power to make up for these mistakes siegel said 
in a statement to the court he pleaded guilty in february 1987 to 
conspiracy to violate securities laws and tax evasion 
in addition to the prison time siegel was sentenced to five 
years probation during which he must perform 3000 hours of 
community service no fine was given 
siegel previously agreed to give up more than 9 million in cash 
and assets to settle civil charges brought by the securities and 
exchange commission 
ward chided siegel for his conduct saying in short there is 
no excuse for what he did what we have here weve seen far 
too many times before in the financial community 
siegels cooperation led to the controversial insider trading 
cases against richard b wigton and timothy l tabor two of 
siegels associates at kidder peabody and freeman formerly head 
of arbitrage at goldman sachs 
the arrests in 1987 of the three traders one being led from his 
office in handcuffs stunned the financial community and led to 
widespread predictions that more wall street professionals would be 
implicated in the scandal 
the government alleged freeman made profitable stock deals on 
inside information about takeover attempts supplied by siegel and 
that wigton and tabor made trading decisions using the tips from 
freeman 
the case eventually was dropped when the government said it 
needed more time to gather evidence but last year after more than 
two years of investigations prosecutors announced they would bring 
no charges against wigton and tabor 
freeman agreed to plead guilty to one count of mail fraud and 
admitted he received inside information in january 1986 from siegel 
and used the tip to execute various trades he was sentenced in 
april to four months in prison and a 1 million fine 
assistant us attorney neil cartusciello recommended siegel 
receive a lesser sentence because he cooperated and freeman did not 
while at first saying siegel should be terribly ashamed for 
what he had done the prosecutor went on to praise his thorough 
and open cooperation 
cartusciello said almost all the information supplied by siegel 
was corroborated independently 
the prosecutor said siegels testimony against freeman was 
especially important because the type of scheme they carried out 
was rarely detected by employers or investigators 
the terms of siegels probation require he perform 2400 hours 
of community service at a community college in jacksonville fla 
where he lives and another 600 hours of community service 
unrelated to his financial skills 
siegel was to surrender at a yet unspecified facility sometime 
before july 15 
according to court papers boesky paid siegel 700000 for stock 
tips over four years the payments were in exchange for information 
he gave boesky about corporate takeover battles he waged as an 
investment banker at kidder peabody 
boesky who pleaded guilty to one felony count to settle the 
biggest insider trading case was recently released after 
completing two years of a threeyear prison sentence 
</TEXT>
