abc on thursday adopted nbcs ratings formula 
for calculating the make good free ad time it gives to 
advertisers on shows delivering lower ratings than the network 
promised 
cbs executives issued a statement at the close of the business 
day in which cbs endorsed nbcs statistical formula but said 
nothing about whether cbs too would adopt the formula in its 
makegood policy 
abc urged unity among advertisers and broadcasters 
a uniform stewardship policy is in the best interest of the 
entire advertising and television network communities abc said 
in a statement released by spokeswoman janice gretemeyer 
cbs had been expected to endorse the plan which comes at the 
start of the fall seasons 4 billion upfront ad market which 
brings in nearly half the 9 billion to 10 billion ad revenue 
estimated the fall season 
all three networks blame this seasons overall ratings decline 
on the people meter system used by the ac nielsen co to 
gather viewership figures in 4000 homes nationwide 
abc initially said it would adjust its ratings based on average 
viewing since 1987 when the people meter became the industry 
standard 
nbc which estimated its loses from lower ratings at 100 
million proposed an eightyear nielsen ratings trend as a 
baseline using a statistical technique called regression 
analysis to project tv usage 
nbc would give away makegood time only when tv usage equals or 
exceeds the prediction derived from nielsens historical data 
if the usage that we find is equal to or greater than our 
forecast then we dont dispute the shortfall and we pay off 
said nick schiavone nbcs vice president for sales and marketing 
research 
cbs without elaboration issued the following statement the 
process of regression analysis as outlined by nbc is in principal 
acceptable to us 
it wasnt immediately clear what the network meant david 
poltrack cbs vice president for research was gone for the day 
and could not be reached for comment said spokeswoman betsy wagner 
nielsen which earns 22 million annually from the three 
networks insists its people meter system is not flawed and that 
fewer people are watching network television 
a viewer in a people meter household logs on to the device 
the previous system recorded what was being viewed but not who was 
watching critics of that system cited button fatigue as the 
cause of inaccurate numbers 
abc said the problem of the unexplained volatility and viewing 
losses reported by nielsen still must be addressed by 
broadcasters advertisers and their agencies 
